INSERT INTO "courses" VALUES(NULL,'AS 16 (Semester Course)','Econometric Methods and Applications I',NULL,'This course gives an introduction to several of the practically most important econometric methods as well as their application to data. The topics covered include:   1)	(The difference  between) causation and Correlation2)	Linear regression (OLS)3)	Nonlinear regression (probit, tobit)4)	Instrumental variables under endogeneity 5)	Sample selection models under non-random sampling6)	Panel data models and Differences in Differences estimation As practical illustration and for further intuition, the contents of the lecture are applied to real data in 5 PC lab sessions using the statistical software R (studio). A short introduction to R (studio) is provided in the first PC lab.','6610-0516','English','Huber M.','Solovyeva A.  Email : anna.solovyeva@unifr.ch','Master',3,4.5,'Students should get familiar with the econometric methods most commonly used in applied work and be able to practically implement the concepts.','Wooldridge, J. M. (2010):  Econometric Analysis of Cross Section and Panel Data, 2nd edition, The MIT Press.','every 2 years','Day Hour Course / Excercise Frequency Room Thursday 10:15 - 13:00 Course weekly PER 21 A230','No restriction','Not authorised','t','Authorised','-','Regulations from May 19th, 2014 on the organisation of assessments at the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the University of Fribourg','Winter  17; Re-assessment 17',NULL,'written exam: and participation in PC labsThe registration period winter period 2017 for the exam will be from September 15th 09:00 to October 14th 2016 12:00 am on mySES.The examinations registration period for the re-assessment period 2017 will be open on mySES from 24th July to 4th August 2017, 12:00 am.	Without registration in the given period, no exam in the choosen period can be taken. Please take note of the deadline.','90 min','English','Valid for the following programmes: Master in Economics; 